Package ru.introguzzle.parsers.json.entity

Class JSONObject

java.lang.Object
ru.introguzzle.parsers.common.util.DelegatingMap<String,Object>
ru.introguzzle.parsers.common.util.UntypedMap
ru.introguzzle.parsers.json.entity.JSONObject
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Consumer<Visitor<JSONObject>>, Map<String,Object>, Visitable<JSONObject,Visitor<JSONObject>>, JSONStringConvertable, JSONObjectConvertable, XMLDocumentConvertable
public class JSONObject extends UntypedMap implements JSONStringConvertable, JSONObjectConvertable, XMLDocumentConvertable, Visitable<JSONObject,Visitor<JSONObject>>, Serializable
Represents a JSON object as a map of key-value pairs.

This class extends UntypedMap and provides methods to access and manipulate JSON data. It implements several interfaces to facilitate conversion to JSON strings, XML documents, and visitation patterns.

Features:

  • Store and retrieve JSON key-value pairs.
  • Access values as specific types (String, Number, Boolean, JSONObject, JSONArray).
  • Convert to JSON string representation.
  • Convert to XML document representation.
  • Flatten nested JSON structures.
  • Bind custom object mappers for specific types.

Usage Example:


 JSONObject jsonObject = new JSONObject();
 jsonObject.put("name", "Alice");
 jsonObject.put("age", 30);
 jsonObject.put("isStudent", false);

 String name = jsonObject.getString("name"); // "Alice"
 int age = jsonObject.getNumber("age").intValue(); // 30
 boolean isStudent = jsonObject.getBoolean("isStudent"); // false

 String jsonString = jsonObject.toJSONString();
 System.out.println(jsonString); // {"name":"Alice","age":30,"isStudent":false}
Note: all methods that are related to storing elements may throw IllegalArgumentException if class of element to be stored is not permitted according to PERMITTED_CLASSES. This behaviour depends on boolean entityValidationEnabled flag in configuration
